# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mixer-rf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A **frequency changer**, or **frequency converter**, is electronic or electromechanical equipment that converts alternating current (AC) of one frequency to alternating current of another frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] The equipment may also change the voltage, but if it does, that is incidental to its principal purpose, since voltage conversion of alternating current is much easier to achieve than frequency conversion.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Traditionally, these were electromechanical machines called motor–generator sets.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] There were also mercury arc rectifiers or vacuum tubes in use.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] With the advent of solid-state electronics, it has become possible to build completely electronic frequency changers.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] These usually consist of a rectifier stage (producing direct current) which is then inverted to produce AC of the desired frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] The inverter may use thyristors, IGCTs or IGBTs.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] If voltage conversion is desired, a transformer will usually be included in either the AC input or output circuitry and this transformer may also provide galvanic isolation between the input and output AC circuits.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A battery may also be added to the DC circuitry to improve the converter's ride-through of brief outages in the input power.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Frequency changers vary in power-handling capability from a few watts to megawatts.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Frequency changers are used for converting bulk AC power from one frequency to another, when two adjacent power grids operate at different utility frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A variable-frequency drive (VFD) is a type of frequency changer used for speed control of AC motors such as used for pumps and fans.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] The speed of a synchronous or induction AC motor is dependent on the frequency of the AC power supply, so changing frequency allows the motor speed to be changed.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] This allows fan or pump output to be varied to match process conditions, which can provide energy savings.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A cycloconverter is also a type of frequency changer.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Unlike a VFD, which is an indirect frequency changer since it uses an AC-DC stage and then a DC-AC stage, a cycloconverter is a direct frequency changer because it uses no intermediate stages.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A cycloconverter can only provide a lower frequency at its output.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Another application is in the aerospace and airline industries.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Often airplanes use 400 Hz power so a 50 Hz or 60 Hz to 400 Hz frequency converter is needed for use in the ground power unit used to power the airplane while it is on the ground.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Airlines might also utilize the converters to provide in-air wall current to passengers for use with laptops and the like.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] Radio and combat systems equipment on Navy warships is often also powered by 400 Hz to reduce noise on the DC signal after rectification.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] In renewable energy systems, frequency converters are an essential component of doubly fed induction generators (DFIGs) as used in modern multi-megawatt class wind turbines.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-changer] A high-voltage direct current system can serve as a frequency converter for large loads.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In electronics, a **mixer** or **frequency mixer** is a circuit that outputs signals with new frequencies from two signals input to it.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In its most common application, two signals are input and two signals are output, having frequencies equal to the sum and the difference of the original frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Other frequency components may also be produced in a practical frequency mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Mixers are widely used to shift signals from one frequency range to another, a process known as *heterodyning*, for convenience in transmission or further signal processing.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] For example, a key component of a superheterodyne receiver is a mixer used to move received signals to a common intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Frequency mixers are also used to modulate a carrier signal in radio transmitters.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The names *detector*, *heterodyne*, *mixer*, and *converter* have overlapped historically, and their meanings have varied with time and context.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In early radio literature, devices that combined two signals to produce new frequencies were often described as *heterodyne detectors* or simply *detectors*, since an important early use was producing audible beat notes from continuous-wave signals.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] As superheterodyne receivers became common, the frequency-changing stage was often called a *converter*, especially when oscillator and mixing functions were combined in one vacuum tube or transistor.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In modern usage, *mixer* is the general term for a circuit that translates frequencies by combining two input signals in a nonlinear manner.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] It can also be analyzed as a linear time-varying system.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The term *mixer* is also used for linear combinations of signals, particularly in audio applications such as mixing consoles.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A superheterodyne receiver uses a mixer to combine the incoming radio-frequency signal (RF) with a local-oscillator (LO).
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] This produces an intermediate frequency (IF), usually fixed, while the oscillator is tuned across the band.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In most designs the IF is the difference between the RF and LO frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] For example, a receiver tuned to 1000 kHz with a 1455 kHz oscillator produces a 455 kHz IF.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The converted signal is then filtered and amplified.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A superheterodyne transmitter uses the same principle in reverse, translating an intermediate-frequency signal to the final transmit frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Mixers were also important in carrier telephony.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Multiple telephone conversations could share one circuit by shifting 300 Hz to 3000 Hz voice channels to higher-frequency slots, such as 56.3 kHz to 59 kHz, then combining them with other channels.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Systems of this kind were in service by 1914 on routes including South Bend, Indiana, and Toledo, Ohio.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In electronic music, nonlinear mixing is commonly known as ring modulation.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Combining two audio signals creates new tones not present in either original signal.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The effect was later used in Moog synthesizer designs.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The mixer circuit can be used not only to shift the frequency of an input signal as in a receiver, but also as a product detector, modulator, phase detector or frequency multiplier.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] For example, a communications receiver might contain two mixer stages for conversion of the input signal to an intermediate frequency and another mixer employed as a detector for demodulation of the signal.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A mixer accepts input signals at frequencies *f*1 and *f*2 and produces output components at new frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The most commonly used are the sum and difference frequencies, *f*1 + *f*2 and $|f_{1}-f_{2}|$ .
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Real circuits also produce additional components of the form $\pm nf_{1}\pm mf_{2}$ , where *m* and *n* are integers.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In most applications, filtering after the mixer determines which of these products is used.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Thus an ideal multiplier produces only sum and difference components, and a following filter selects the desired output.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In a superheterodyne receiver, one input is the RF signal and the other is the local-oscillator; the selected output is the intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Desirable mixer characteristics in this application include low local-oscillator feedthrough, linear conversion of the RF input, low added noise, and good immunity to strong nearby signals.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In integrated circuits, a Gilbert cell is a common mixer topology.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] When driven strongly by the local-oscillator, it approximates switching multiplication.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Early mixers commonly worked by adding the two input signals and applying the combined waveform to a nonlinear device such as a crystal detector, diode, or vacuum tube.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Because of the nonlinear transfer characteristic, the output contained sum and difference frequencies together with harmonics and intermodulation products.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Early analyses distinguished between *linear-law* operation, where the device characteristic is approximately proportional, and *square-law* operation, where the output is proportional to the square of the input, producing strong second-order mixing products.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The 1924 RCA Radiola superheterodynes used the Houck mixer, which employed the second harmonic of the local-oscillator for frequency conversion.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Houck developed the circuit to overcome limitations of early vacuum tubes.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The essential characteristic of a mixer is that it produces a component in its output which is the non-linear function of the two input signals.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Both active and passive circuits can realize mixers.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Passive mixers use one or more diodes and rely on their nonlinear current–voltage relationship.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In a passive mixer, the desired output signal is always of lower power than the input signals.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Active mixers use an amplifying device (such as a transistor or vacuum tube) that may increase the strength of the product signal.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Active mixers improve isolation between the ports, but may have higher noise, more distortion and power consumption.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] An active mixer can be less linear, especially less tolerant of overload.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Mixers may be built of discrete components, may be part of integrated circuits, or can be delivered as hybrid modules.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Selection of a mixer type is a trade-off for a particular application.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] An unbalanced mixer uses a nonlinear element applied to the sum of the two inputs.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The original input signals typically appear at the output along with the desired products.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Simple diode, transistor, and vacuum-tube mixers are examples.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] These circuits are simple and may provide conversion gain, but usually require output filtering to suppress unwanted components.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Vacuum tubes were later developed that more closely approximated multiplicative mixing.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Examples include pentagrid and heptode converter tubes such as the 6L7.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Balanced mixers use circuit symmetry so that one or both input signals are substantially cancelled at the output while the desired products remain.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] This reduces local-oscillator feedthrough, radiation, and unwanted distortion.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Balanced arrangements were well established by the 1930s in telephone carrier systems.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A *single-balanced mixer* suppresses one input signal, typically the local-oscillator.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In 1921, a balanced modulator using dual triodes was described for carrier telephony.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Single-balanced mixers also cancel, or strongly suppress, many even-order distortion products associated with the local-oscillator, while reducing local-oscillator signal at the output.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Beam-deflection tubes such as the 7360 approximated a single-balanced mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A *double-balanced mixer* suppresses both inputs from the output and passes primarily the sum and difference products.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] This reduces many unwanted components while preserving the desired frequency translation.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In diode-ring mixers the diodes are commonly Schottky types.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Such mixers are widely used because of their low feedthrough, broad frequency range, and good large-signal performance.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Bell System research in the late 1920s examined double-balanced mixers using copper-oxide rectifiers for voice modulation.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] By 1931 they were reported as serious competitors to vacuum-tube modulators, and by 1939 they were used in many telephony carrier systems.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] These circuits translated voice channels to higher carrier frequencies so that multiple conversations could share one transmission path.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Systems carrying up to 60 voice channels in a 240 kHz band were reported.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The four-rectifier ring circuit provided approximately 20-30 dB suppression of unwanted feedthrough and was described as a double-balanced reversing-switch modulator, or ring modulator in German literature.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Balanced mixers can also be built from active devices such as transistors or MOSFETs.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] An ISSCC paper in 1968 described a symmetric MOSFET mixer with about 40 dB better performance than a typical communications receiver of the period.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] As with earlier vacuum-tube converter circuits, an integrated double-balanced mixer can also incorporate local-oscillator generation.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A 1.5 mW combination of a low-noise amplifier, oscillator, and mixer was reported in a 65 nm CMOS process.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Mixer circuits are characterized by their properties such as conversion gain (or loss), noise figure and nonlinearity.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Nonlinear electronic components that are used as mixers include diodes and transistors biased near cutoff.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Linear, time-varying devices, such as analog multipliers, provide superior performance, as it is only in true multipliers that the output amplitude is proportional to the input amplitude, as required for linear conversion.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Ferromagnetic-core inductors driven into saturation have also been used.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In nonlinear optics, crystals with nonlinear characteristics are used to mix two frequencies of laser light to create optical heterodynes.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A diode can be used to create a simple unbalanced mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] where $I_{\mathrm {S} }$ is the saturation current, q is the charge of an electron, n is the nonideality factor, k is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the absolute temperature.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The ellipsis represents all higher powers of the sum.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Suppose that the sum of the two input signals $v_{1}{+}v_{2}$ is applied to a diode, and that an output voltage is generated that is proportional to the current through the diode (perhaps by providing the voltage that is present across a resistor in series with the diode).
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] These new frequencies are *in addition to* the original frequencies of a and b .
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] A narrowband filter may be used to remove undesired frequencies from the output signal.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] Another form of mixer operates by switching, which is equivalent to multiplication of an input signal by a square wave.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In a double-balanced mixer, the (smaller) input signal is alternately inverted or non inverted according to the phase of the local-oscillator (LO).
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] That is, the input signal is effectively multiplied by a square wave that alternates between +1 and -1 at the LO rate.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In a single-balanced switching mixer, the input signal is alternately passed or blocked.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The input signal is thus effectively multiplied by a square wave that alternates between 0 and +1.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] This results in frequency components of the input signal being present in the output together with the product, since the multiplying signal can be viewed as a square wave with a DC offset (i.e. a zero frequency component).
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The aim of a switching mixer is to achieve the linear operation by means of hard switching, driven by the local-oscillator.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] In the frequency domain, the switching mixer operation leads to the usual sum and difference frequencies, but also to further terms e.g. ±3*f*LO, ±5*f*LO, etc.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] The advantage of a switching mixer is that it can achieve (with the same effort) a lower noise figure (NF) and larger conversion gain.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] This is because the switching diodes or transistors act either like a small resistor (switch closed) or large resistor (switch open), and in both cases only a minimal noise is added.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] From the circuit perspective, many multiplying mixers can be used as switching mixers, just by increasing the LO amplitude.
[src:mixer-rf/frequency-mixer] So RF engineers simply talk about mixers, while they mean switching mixers.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] In electronics, the **Gilbert cell** is a type of frequency mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] It produces output signals proportional to the product of two input signals.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Such circuits are widely used for frequency conversion in radio systems.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] The advantage of this circuit is the output current is an accurate multiplication of the (differential) base currents of both inputs.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] As a mixer, its balanced operation cancels out many unwanted mixing products, resulting in a "cleaner" output.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Gilbert cells can also be used as variable-gain amplifiers (VGA).
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] It is a generalized case of an early circuit first used by Howard Jones in 1963, invented independently and greatly augmented by Barrie Gilbert in 1967.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] It is a specific example of "translinear" design, a current-mode approach to analog circuit design.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] The specific property of this cell is that the differential output current is a precise algebraic product of its two differential analog current inputs.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] There is little difference between the Jones cell and the translinear multiplier in this topology.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] In both forms, two differential amplifier stages are formed by emitter-coupled transistor pairs (Q1/Q4, Q3/Q5) whose outputs are connected (currents summed) with opposite phases.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] The emitter junctions of these amplifier stages are fed by the collectors of a third differential pair (Q2/Q6).
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] The output currents of Q2/Q6 become emitter currents for the differential amplifiers.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Simplified, the output current of an individual transistor is given by ic = gm vbe.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Its transconductance gm is (at T = 300 K) about gm = 40 IC.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Combining these equations gives ic = 40 IC vbe,lo.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] However, IC here is given by vbe,rf gm,rf.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Hence ic = 40 vbe,lo vbe,rf gm,rf, which is a multiplication of vbe,lo and vbe,rf.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Combining the two different stages output currents yields four-quadrant operation.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Specifically, the differential output current would now be proportional to the product of an *arbitrary* number of differential inputs (or some translinear function thereof).
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] However, the utility of this generalization in practical microelectronics settings is limited due to the large voltage headroom needed to keep all of the transistors in the proper (forward-active) region of operation.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] However, in the cells later invented by Gilbert, shown in the figure on the right, there are two additional diode-connected transistors (labeled as V1 and V2).
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] This is a crucial difference because they generate the logarithm of the associated differential (X) input current so that the exponential characteristics of the following transistors result in an ideally perfect multiplication of these input currents with the remaining pair of (Y) currents.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] This additional diode cell topology is typically used when a low distortion voltage-controlled amplifier (VCA) is required.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] This topology is rarely used in RF mixer/modulator applications for various reasons, one being that the linearity advantage of the top linearized cascode is minimal due to the near-square wave drive signals to these bases.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] The drive is less likely to be a fast-edge squarewave at very high frequencies when there may be some advantage in the linearization.
[src:mixer-rf/gilbert-cell] Nowadays, functionally similar circuits can be constructed using CMOS or BiCMOS cells.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A **heterodyne** is the result of mixing two signals in a nonlinear device to produce new frequency components, notably sum and difference frequencies of the original signals.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This process, called **heterodyning**, is fundamental to signal processing and radio systems.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In a typical implementation, signals at frequencies *f*₁ and *f*₂ are applied to a nonlinear element such as a frequency mixer, producing components at *f*₁ + *f*₂ and *f*₁ − *f*₂, along with additional intermodulation products arising from the device nonlinearity.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] One of these components is selected by filtering for further use, while the others are rejected.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Heterodyning is not limited to radio frequencies; the same principle applies across the electromagnetic spectrum, including infrared and optical systems, where it is used in coherent detection techniques.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Heterodyne frequencies are related to the phenomenon of *beats* in acoustics.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A major application of the heterodyne process is in the superheterodyne radio receiver circuit, which is used in virtually all modern radio receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In 1901, Reginald Fessenden demonstrated a direct-conversion receiver or beat receiver as a method of making continuous wave radiotelegraphy signals audible.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Fessenden's receiver did not see much application because of its local oscillator's stability problem.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A stable yet inexpensive local oscillator was not available until Lee de Forest invented the triode vacuum tube oscillator.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In a 1905 patent, Fessenden stated that the frequency stability of his local oscillator was one part per thousand.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In radio telegraphy, the characters of text messages are translated into the short duration dots and long duration dashes of Morse code that are broadcast as radio signals.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Radio telegraphy was much like ordinary telegraphy.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] One of the problems was building high power transmitters with the technology of the day.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Early transmitters were spark gap transmitters.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A mechanical device would make sparks at a fixed but audible rate; the sparks would put energy into a resonant circuit that would then ring at the desired transmission frequency (which might be 100 kHz).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This ringing would quickly decay, so the output of the transmitter would be a succession of damped waves.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] When these damped waves were received by a simple detector, the operator would hear an audible buzzing sound that could be transcribed back into alpha-numeric characters.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] With the development of the arc converter radio transmitter in 1904, continuous wave (CW) modulation began to be used for radiotelegraphy.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] CW Morse code signals are not amplitude modulated, but rather consist of bursts of sinusoidal carrier frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] When CW signals are received by an AM receiver, the operator does not hear a sound.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The direct-conversion (heterodyne) detector was invented to make continuous wave radio-frequency signals audible.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The *heterodyne* or *beat* receiver has a local oscillator that produces a radio signal adjusted to be close in frequency to the incoming signal being received.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] When the two signals are mixed, a *beat* frequency equal to the difference between the two frequencies is created.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Adjusting the local oscillator frequency correctly puts the beat frequency in the audio range, where it can be heard as a tone in the receiver's earphones whenever the transmitter signal is present.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Thus the Morse code dots and dashes are audible as beeping sounds.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This technique is still used in radio telegraphy, the local oscillator now being called the beat frequency oscillator or BFO.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Fessenden coined the word *heterodyne* from the Greek roots *hetero-*, different, and *dyn-*, power (cf. δύναμις or dunamis).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] An important and widely used application of the heterodyne technique is in the superheterodyne receiver (superhet).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In the typical superhet, the incoming radio frequency signal from the antenna is mixed (heterodyned) with a signal from a local oscillator (LO) to produce a lower fixed frequency signal called the intermediate frequency (IF) signal.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The IF signal is amplified and filtered and then applied to a detector that extracts the audio signal; the audio is ultimately sent to the receiver's loudspeaker.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The superheterodyne receiver has several advantages over previous receiver designs.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] One advantage is easier tuning; only the RF filter and the LO are tuned by the operator; the fixed-frequency IF is tuned ("aligned") at the factory and is not adjusted.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In older designs such as the tuned radio frequency receiver (TRF), all of the receiver stages had to be simultaneously tuned.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In addition, since the IF filters are fixed-tuned, the receiver's selectivity is the same across the receiver's entire frequency band.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Another advantage is that the IF signal can be at a much lower frequency than the incoming radio signal, and that allows each stage of the IF amplifier to provide more gain.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] To first order, an amplifying device has a fixed gain-bandwidth product.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] If the device has a gain-bandwidth product of 60 MHz, then it can provide a voltage gain of 3 at an RF of 20 MHz or a voltage gain of 30 at an IF of 2 MHz.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] At a lower IF, it would take fewer gain devices to achieve the same gain.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The regenerative radio receiver obtained more gain out of one gain device by using positive feedback, but it required careful adjustment by the operator; that adjustment also changed the selectivity of the regenerative receiver.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The superheterodyne provides a large, stable gain and constant selectivity without troublesome adjustment.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The superior superheterodyne system replaced the earlier TRF and regenerative receiver designs, and since the 1930s most commercial radio receivers have been superheterodynes.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Heterodyning, also called *frequency conversion*, is used very widely in communications engineering to generate new frequencies and move information from one frequency channel to another.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This is called frequency division multiplexing (FDM).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] For example, a coaxial cable used by a cable television system can carry 500 television channels at the same time because each one is given a different frequency, so they do not interfere with one another.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] At the cable source or headend, electronic upconverters convert each incoming television channel to a new, higher frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] They do this by mixing the television signal frequency, *fCH* with a local oscillator at a much higher frequency *fLO*, creating a heterodyne at the sum *fCH* + *fLO*, which is added to the cable.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Each channel is moved to a different higher frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The original lower basic frequency of the signal is called the baseband, while the higher channel it is moved to is called the passband.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Many analog videotape systems rely on a downconverted color subcarrier to record color information in their limited bandwidth.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] These systems are referred to as *heterodyne systems* or *color-under systems*.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] For instance, for NTSC video systems, the VHS (and S-VHS) recording system converts the color subcarrier from the NTSC standard 3.58 MHz to ~629 kHz.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] PAL VHS color subcarrier is similarly downconverted (but from 4.43 MHz).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Other videotape formats with heterodyne color systems include Video-8 and Hi8.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The heterodyne system in these cases is used to convert quadrature phase-encoded and amplitude modulated sine waves from the broadcast frequencies to frequencies recordable in less than 1 MHz bandwidth.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] On playback, the recorded color information is heterodyned back to the standard subcarrier frequencies for display on televisions and for interchange with other standard video equipment.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Some U-matic (3/4″) decks feature 7-pin mini-DIN connectors to allow dubbing of tapes without conversion, as do some industrial VHS, S-VHS, and Hi8 recorders.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The theremin, an electronic musical instrument, traditionally uses the heterodyne principle to produce a variable audio frequency in response to the movement of the musician's hands in the vicinity of one or more antennas, which act as capacitor plates.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The output of a fixed radio frequency oscillator is mixed with that of an oscillator whose frequency is affected by the variable capacitance between the antenna and the musician's hand as it is moved near the pitch control antenna.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The difference between the two oscillator frequencies produces a tone in the audio range.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The ring modulator is a type of frequency mixer incorporated into some synthesizers or used as a stand-alone audio effect.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Optical heterodyne detection (an area of active research) is an extension of the heterodyning technique to higher (visible) frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Guerra (1995) first published the results of what he called a "form of optical heterodyning" in which light patterned by a 50 nm pitch grating illuminated a second grating of pitch 50 nm, with the gratings rotated with respect to each other by the angular amount needed to achieve magnification.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Although the illuminating wavelength was 650 nm, the 50 nm grating was easily resolved.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This showed a nearly 5-fold improvement over the Abbe resolution limit of 232 nm that should have been the smallest obtained for the numerical aperture and wavelength used.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This super-resolution microscopic imaging through optical heterodyning later came to be known by many as *structured illumination microscopy*.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In addition to super-resolution optical microscopy, optical heterodyning could greatly improve optical modulators, increasing the density of information carried by optical fibers.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] It is also being applied in the creation of more accurate atomic clocks based on directly measuring the frequency of a laser beam.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Since optical frequencies are far beyond the manipulation capacity of any feasible electronic circuit, all visible frequency photon detectors are inherently energy detectors not oscillating electric field detectors.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] However, since energy detection is inherently square-law detection, it intrinsically mixes any optical frequencies present on the detector.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Thus, sensitive detection of specific optical frequencies necessitates optical heterodyne detection, in which two different (close by) wavelengths of light illuminate the detector so that the oscillating electrical output corresponds to the difference between their frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This allows extremely narrow band detection (much narrower than any possible color filter can achieve) as well as precision measurements of phase and frequency of a light signal relative to a reference light source, as in a laser Doppler vibrometer.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] This phase sensitive detection has been applied for Doppler measurements of wind speed, and imaging through dense media.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The high sensitivity against background light is especially useful for lidar.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In optical Kerr effect (OKE) spectroscopy, optical heterodyning of the OKE signal and a small part of the probe signal produces a mixed signal consisting of probe, heterodyne OKE-probe and homodyne OKE signal.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The probe and homodyne OKE signals can be filtered out, leaving the heterodyne frequency signal for detection.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Heterodyne detection is often used in interferometry but usually confined to single point detection rather than widefield interferometry, however, widefield heterodyne interferometry is possible using a special camera.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Using this technique which a reference signal extracted from a single pixel it is possible to build a highly stable widefield heterodyne interferometer by removing the piston phase component caused by microphonics or vibrations of the optical components or object.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The product on the left hand side represents the multiplication ("mixing") of a sine wave with another sine wave (both produced by cosine functions).
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The result is the sum of two sinusoidal signals, one at the sum *f*1 + *f*2 and one at the difference *f*1 − *f*2 of the original frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] The two signals are combined in a device called a *mixer*.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] As seen in the previous section, an ideal mixer would be a device that multiplies the two signals.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Some widely used mixer circuits, such as the Gilbert cell, operate in this way, but they are limited to lower frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] However, any *nonlinear* electronic component also multiplies signals applied to it, producing heterodyne frequencies in its output—so a variety of nonlinear components serve as mixers.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A nonlinear component is one in which the output current or voltage is a nonlinear function of its input.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Most circuit elements in communications circuits are designed to be linear.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] So if two sine wave signals at frequencies *f*1 and *f*2 are applied to a linear device, the output is simply the sum of the outputs when the two signals are applied separately with no product terms.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Thus, the function F must be nonlinear to create mixer products.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] A perfect multiplier only produces mixer products at the sum and difference frequencies (*f*1 ± *f*2), but more general nonlinear functions produce higher order mixer products: *n*⋅*f*1 + *m*⋅*f*2 for integers *n* and *m*.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Some mixer designs, such as double-balanced mixers, suppress some high order undesired products, while other designs, such as harmonic mixers exploit high order differences.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Examples of nonlinear components that are used as mixers are vacuum tubes and transistors biased near cutoff (class C), and diodes.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] Ferromagnetic core inductors driven into saturation can also be used at lower frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] In nonlinear optics, crystals that have nonlinear characteristics are used to mix laser light beams to create optical heterodyne frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] To simplify the math, the higher order terms above *α*2 are indicated by an ellipsis ( $\ \cdots \$ ) and only the first terms are shown.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] It can be seen that the second term above contains a product of the two sine waves.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] It also contains much more complicated terms at frequencies of *M ω*1 + *N ω*2 , called intermodulation products.
[src:mixer-rf/heterodyne] These unwanted frequencies, along with the unwanted heterodyne frequency, must be removed from the mixer output by an electronic filter, to leave the desired heterodyne frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The **superheterodyne receiver**, commonly called the **superhet**, is a radio receiver that uses heterodyning to convert incoming radio-frequency (RF) signals to a fixed intermediate frequency (IF).
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The signal is then amplified and filtered at that fixed frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This arrangement separates tuning from most of the gain and filtering: the RF circuits make an initial, relatively broad selection of the desired station, while the IF stages provide most of the amplification and the selectivity needed to separate it from adjacent stations.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The design became important during the rapid growth of broadcast radio in the 1920s.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As amplitude modulation (AM) stations multiplied, receivers had to handle crowded bands and signals that ranged from strong local stations to weak distant ones.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Many earlier sets required several tuning controls to be adjusted together, and their performance varied widely.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The superheterodyne offered a more practical path to stable gain, sharper selectivity, and simpler operation, especially as vacuum tubes (valves) improved and became cheaper.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The principle had been developed earlier, but the superheterodyne did not become widely used until the mid-1920s, when receiver designs and vacuum tubes improved enough for practical mass production.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Patent control and licensing also played a role.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The Radio Corporation of America (RCA) and associated companies held key rights and influenced which receiver types could be manufactured.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the early 1930s, as licensing issues eased, the superheterodyne largely replaced earlier receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Radio direction-finding (RDF) required the accurate amplification of weak signals.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] RDF equipment used in World War I operated at frequencies from about 50 kHz to 2 MHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Armstrong stated that the motivation for the superheterodyne was to extend the usable frequency range of such systems, allowing reception of higher-frequency emissions, such as those from aircraft ignition.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Incoming radio signals are very weak, and early sets were limited by the available means of amplification.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Crystal detector receivers provided rectification without gain and were widely used in inexpensive sets produced by companies such as Crosley.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The introduction of the audion (triode) made amplification possible and enabled louder reception, but early vacuum tubes were expensive and had limited performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Much of early receiver architecture was driven by the cost of gain; in 1920 a triode cost $7.00, about $113 now.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Receiver performance is commonly described in terms of sensitivity, selectivity, fidelity, distortion, and noise.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Sensitivity is the ability to receive weak signals at a usable level, while selectivity is the ability to discriminate the desired signal from signals at other frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Fidelity and distortion describe the accuracy of the recovered audio, while receiver noise limits the weakest signal that can be used.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Herold described the years from about 1907 to 1927 as the first major period of vacuum-tube development.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early triodes allowed amplification, oscillation, regeneration, heterodyning, and the superheterodyne.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Receiver design during this period was shaped by what could be done with early tubes and by how much performance could be obtained from a small number of them.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Broadcasting expanded rapidly, increasing the number of stations and available programs.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Westinghouse entered broadcasting after Frank Conrad began transmitting from his home soon after World War I.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The number of U.S. broadcasting stations grew from five in 1921 to 530 in 1924.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the late 1920s, the growth of broadcasting placed greater demands on receiver performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As one contemporary review observed, “receivers which were giving satisfactory service at the beginning of that period are now obsolete.” The increasing number of stations required greater selectivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Reception of distant stations and the use of practical household antennas kept sensitivity important, while improved programs and loudspeakers raised expectations for audio fidelity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] At the same time, vacuum tubes improved and became less expensive.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As tubes became cheaper, the extra stages required by the superheterodyne became less of an economic disadvantage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Improved tubes also made stable gain, single-control tuning, and automatic gain control more practical, helping the superheterodyne become the standard broadcast receiver architecture.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the late 1910s, heterodyne reception was understood as a method of frequency conversion, and the use of vacuum tubes made it possible to generate local oscillations within the receiver.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] It was also recognized that amplification was easier at lower frequencies with the tubes then available, and that stable, high-gain amplification was difficult when the tuned frequency had to be varied across a wide range.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Developments in the superheterodyne receiver and carrier telephony were closely related.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Both depended on heterodyning, filters, and stable amplification, and many of the theoretical and practical advances originated from the same research efforts.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A practical approach was to convert the received signal to a fixed intermediate frequency before amplification.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The incoming signal was combined with a locally generated oscillation (LO) in a mixer stage (often called the first detector), producing sum and difference frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The difference frequency, termed the intermediate frequency (IF), retained the original signal information while shifting it to a frequency more suitable for amplification and filtering.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Heterodyne reception was already present in earlier vacuum-tube designs.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] What distinguished the superheterodyne was the selection of a fixed intermediate frequency above the audio range, allowing subsequent stages to be optimized for a single frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In early conference disscusion, engineers noted that heterodyne frequencies need not be audible.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] After conversion, the signal was filtered and amplified at the intermediate frequency, detected to recover the audio, and further amplified for output.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This separated tuning from amplification, allowing most of the receiver to operate at a fixed frequency without the need to retune high-selectivity stages.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Selectivity was largely set in the intermediate-frequency stages, where more elaborate tuned circuits could be used without the need for adjustment.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A 1921 article in QST showed how to use a 55 kHz tuned radio frequency receiver as a super-heterodyne by adding a tube as an oscillator (LO) and one as a detector.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Frequencies between 375 kHz and 2 MHz could be received.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Multigrid tubes, particularly the screen-grid tetrode, improved both RF and IF amplification.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The early superheterodyne required additional circuitry for frequency conversion and a local oscillator, making it more expensive than simpler receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Although it offered greater sensitivity and easier tuning, these advantages did not initially displace tuned radio-frequency receivers, which remained common through the 1920s.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The introduction of the pentagrid converter around 1933 reduced the tube count and made inexpensive superheterodyne receivers practical.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A shift occurred in 1923, when David Sarnoff of RCA observed a superheterodyne receiver incorporating improvements by Harry Houck and cancelled existing receiver production orders, replacing them with superheterodyne designs.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Houck’s work addressed practical limitations of earlier superheterodyne receivers, particularly in the generation and coupling of the local oscillator signal.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] These changes allowed consistent frequency conversion and reliable operation in production sets, and were credited with making the superheterodyne suitable for manufacture rather than limited to experimental use.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early superheterodyne receivers typically used low intermediate frequencies due to the limitations of triode amplifiers at radio frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] While this allowed stable amplification, it also resulted in poor image rejection and increased susceptibility to interference.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As improved vacuum tubes became available, higher intermediate frequencies were adopted, improving performance in increasingly crowded broadcast bands.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Ease of operation mattered in commercial adoption.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early receivers often required the adjustment of several tuning controls, each modifying different tuned circuits.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Selecting a station with a single-control tuning was a clear improvement.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Earlier work on simplified tuning had been described by John L.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Hogan, and by the mid-1920s practical single-dial superheterodyne designs were being published.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early sets relied on expensive batteries, but during the late 1920s battery eliminators and, later, line-powered receivers reduced operating cost.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Houck was also involved in this transition; contemporary accounts describe litigation with Cornell-Dubilier over battery eliminator technology with damages reported at approximately $20 million, showing the commercial importance of these developments.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Control of signal strength became increasingly important with some signals being much stronger than others.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By 1930, improved vacuum tubes such as the screen-grid tetrode were incorporated into superheterodyne receivers, further improving gain and stability.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] During the same period, RCA expanded licensing of superheterodyne patents to other manufacturers amid antitrust pressures, extending access to the design while maintaining royalty arrangements.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The superheterodyne receiver played a significant role in the complex patents and licensing in early radio.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] " AM broadcast receiver from 1940s was inexpensive because it only required five tubes and did not use a power supply transformer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The pentagrid converter tube further reduced the price of a superheterodyne radio, enabling the "All-American Five" receiver, using only five tubes: usually a converter (mixer/local oscillator), an IF amplifier, a detector/audio amplifier, audio power amplifier, and a rectifier.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Converter tubes reduced cost and parts count by combining oscillator and mixer functions in one tube.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Herold described the pentagrid converter as the most satisfactory of the earlier multigrid converter tubes and noted that it remained widely used.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Since the mid 1930s the superheterodyne design was used for almost all commercial radio and TV receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Up to 1930, non-superheterodyne receivers still dominated the market.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By 1933, however, superheterodyne sets accounted for 96 percent of sales.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A contemporary study of interference effects therefore concluded that only superheterodyne receivers needed to be considered.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The superheterodyne became dominant because it separated functions that proved difficult to perform together.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Earlier receivers had to amplify, select, and tune the signal at the received frequency, often requiring several tuned stages to track together.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By moving most amplification and filtering to a fixed intermediate frequency, the superheterodyne made gain, selectivity, and stability easier to obtain.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Higher-order filters could be used at the fixed IF, while the RF stages only needed to make a coarser initial selection.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] These advantages became clear as broadcast bands became crowded.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early superheterodyne receivers were expensive because they required extra tubes, including a local oscillator and mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As vacuum tubes improved and became cheaper, this disadvantage became less important.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Radios became easier to use as single-control tuning and automatic volume control reduced knobs and adjustments.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Herold later identified the years from about 1927 to 1936 as the period when the superheterodyne became the universal receiver circuit.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Better tubes made AC operation, single-knob tuning, automatic gain control, and multigrid converter stages practical.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Those changes removed much of the early penalty for using a more complex receiver, while preserving the superheterodyne's advantages in gain and selectivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Commercial adoption was also shaped by RCA licensing.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Converter tubes combined the oscillator and mixer, reducing cost.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Low-cost superheterodynes such as the All American Five proliferated as the superheterodyne became the standard.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The heterodyne method of reception was described by Fessenden in 1905, 1908 and 1912 patents.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] It was described as a way of making continuous signals audible by offsetting the frequencies of two ends of a communications link, and using a generator at each end as both a transmitter and a heterodyne source for receiving.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In 1913 it was described as a method of achieving apparent signal amplification.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Hogan Jr. described heterodyne reception in terms of generating beat frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] When asked about using heterodyning for telephony by Robert Marriott, Hogan responded that the beat frequency would be at a frequency above hearing.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By 1915, the vacuum tube used as an oscillator expanded the use of heterodyne methods.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Hogan described receivers in which a single vacuum tube could simultaneously generate oscillations, detect signals, and provide amplification, while noting that the combined action of these processes made the underlying behavior difficult to analyze.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Patents also described the use of locally generated oscillations to improve detection, but did not include selective intermediate-frequency stages or amplification at the converted frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In a 1916 patent application, Langmuir describes using a single triode as both the oscillator and the detector.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Use of a heterodyne frequency above the audio band was known, as he states "Since in most cases it will be desirable to employ frequencies beyond the range of audibility of a telephone receiver".
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This reflects an early recognition that the heterodyne process need not produce an audible output directly.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A central question in this period was whether heterodyne reception itself provided amplification.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Benjamin Liebowitz analyzed the method mathematically in 1915, concluding that gain was not inherent in the process itself, but attributed the observed effects to detector nonlinearity rather than frequency conversion itself.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In 1917, Edwin Howard Armstrong showed that heterodyne reception could produce amplification when the detector operated in a square-law region, with conversion gain a function of the amplitude of the local oscillator, and limited by tube characteristics.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Howe in 1918, who confirmed Armstrong's results mathematically.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Carson provided a more general theoretical treatment of the three-element vacuum tube, showing similar results.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the end of this period, the heterodyne process was understood as a form of nonlinear frequency conversion in which gain could be obtained under specific operating conditions.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Conversion to super-audio frequencies had been discussed, but the use of a fixed intermediate frequency for further processing as the basis of a receiver architecture had not yet been developed.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] French engineer Lucien Lévy filed a patent application for the superheterodyne principle in August 1917 with brevet n° 493660.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Armstrong also filed his patent in 1917.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Lévy filed his original disclosure about seven months before Armstrong's.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Schottky also filed a related patent in 1918.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] At first the United States recognized Armstrong as the inventor, and his U.S.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] After various changes and court hearings Lévy was awarded U.S. patent No.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] 1,734,938 that included seven of the nine claims in Armstrong's application, while the two remaining claims were granted to Ernst Alexanderson of GE and AT&T's Kendall.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Later commentary distinguished between patent disclosure and practical development, and in practice the superheterodyne was adopted through cross-licensing among major manufacturers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Contemporary technical commentary reflected a distinction between legal priority and practical development.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In 1926, Walter Schottky stated that Lévy’s patent described the essential elements of the method and therefore represented its origin from a patent-law perspective, while attributing the practical development of the superheterodyne receiver to Armstrong and his collaborators.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] RCA’s licensing policy also shaped adoption.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In 1927, the company licensed the Neutrodyne circuit to other manufacturers, while superheterodyne rights remained more restricted.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] After the suicide of Armstrong in 1954, Lévy wrote "If I may be permitted, in remembering with emotion the memory of E.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A superheterodyne receiver converts an incoming radio-frequency signal to a fixed intermediate frequency, where most of the amplification and selectivity are applied.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The received signal from the antenna is first filtered, then combined with a locally generated oscillator signal in a mixer to produce new frequencies equal to the sum and difference of the two.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] One of these, the intermediate frequency, is selected and amplified by tuned stages optimized for a single frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The modulation is then recovered by a detector and passed to an audio or other output stage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By concentrating gain and filtering at a fixed frequency rather than at the received frequency, the superheterodyne design allows consistent selectivity and sensitivity over a wide tuning range.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The medium-wave broadcast band spans 531–1602 kHz in Europe, using 9 kHz channel spacing, and 540–1700 kHz in North America, using 10 kHz spacing.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the mid-1930s, an intermediate frequency of 455 kHz had become widely adopted for broadcast receivers, as it provided a practical balance between image rejection and achievable selectivity with tuned circuits.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In a typical arrangement the local oscillator is operated above the received frequency (high-side injection), so that the intermediate frequency is given by *f*IF = *f*LO − *f*RF.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The resulting frequency relationships at the lower and upper ends of the band are shown below.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Across the band, the local oscillator must tune from approximately 986 kHz to 2155 kHz, a range slightly greater than 2:1.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] If low-side injection were used instead, the oscillator would have to tune from 76 kHz to 1245 kHz, a much wider ratio that is difficult to realize with a single tuned circuit.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This is one reason high-side injection became standard in broadcast receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF tuned circuits are primarily responsible for attenuating relatively distant interferers, including the image frequency, while the IF stages provide most of the selectivity against nearby channels.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This separation allows each stage to be optimized for a different problem: the RF stage for image rejection over a wide frequency range, and the IF stage for narrowband selectivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The image frequency is separated from the desired signal by twice the intermediate frequency (2 × 455 kHz = 910 kHz).
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] At the upper end of the band this places the image well above the broadcast band, while at the lower end it falls within the band.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF input circuit must therefore attenuate these image frequencies while still passing the desired signal, which requires the RF tuning to track the local oscillator.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Because broadcast channels are spaced only 9 or 10 kHz apart, the selectivity cannot be achieved without multiple LC circuits, which would be impractical to implement in a tuned RF stage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Instead, the superheterodyne architecture concentrates gain and filtering at the fixed intermediate frequency, where multiple tuned stages can be optimized to separate the desired channel from adjacent ones.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF stage then serves primarily to limit image response and strong out-of-band signals, while tracking the local oscillator as the receiver is tuned across the band.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF stage provides the initial frequency-selective filtering and, in some designs, gain for the received signal.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Its primary function is to attenuate the image frequency and other out-of-band signals that would otherwise be converted to the intermediate frequency by the mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This operation is often called preselection.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The filtering is typically provided by one or more tuned circuits.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In receivers that tune over a wide frequency range, the RF tuning tracks the local oscillator so that both remain tuned together as the receiver is tuned.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This tracking may be achieved with mechanically ganged variable capacitors or electronically using varicap diodes.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] An RF amplifier may be included to improve sensitivity, but at lower frequencies it is often unnecessary when external noise exceeds the internal noise of the receiver.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In such cases the RF stage provides little or no gain, and most of the amplification is obtained at the intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF stage must also remain sufficiently linear to handle strong signals without overload.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Nonlinear operation can produce intermodulation products that fall within the passband and interfere with reception of nearby channels.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In earlier tuned radio-frequency (TRF) receivers, all gain and selectivity were applied at the received frequency, requiring multiple tuned stages to track together.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The superheterodyne instead concentrates most of the gain and selectivity at a fixed intermediate frequency, allowing higher overall gain with improved stability.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The total voltage gain of a receiver, from microvolt-level input signals to several volts at the audio output, may exceed 100 dB.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In the superheterodyne this gain is distributed between RF and IF stages, reducing the likelihood of instability due to unintended feedback.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The RF stage also serves to limit radiation of the local oscillator signal from the antenna, which could otherwise cause interference to nearby receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Herold described frequency conversion in superheterodyne receivers as a modulation process in which the local oscillator periodically varies the transconductance of the signal path, producing an intermediate-frequency output.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The received signal is combined with a signal from a local oscillator (LO) in a nonlinear device called a mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The mixer produces signal frequencies at the sum and difference of its input frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Those signals each carry the original modulation.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] For an input at $f_{\mathrm {RF} }$ and an oscillator at $f_{\mathrm {LO} }$ , the principal outputs are $f_{\mathrm {RF} }+f_{\mathrm {LO} }$ and $\left|f_{\mathrm {RF} }-f_{\mathrm {LO} }\right|$ .
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In an ideal multiplier driven by a sinusoidal LO, only these two components are produced, but practical mixers also generate higher-order intermodulation products.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early mixers summed the LO and RF signals into a nonlinear device, usually square-law, to do the conversion.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Modern IC mixers use a balanced mixer configuration to produce fewer interference products.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] If $f_{\mathrm {LO} }>f_{\mathrm {RF} }$ , the arrangement is called *high-side injection*; if $f_{\mathrm {LO} }<f_{\mathrm {RF} }$ , it is *low-side injection*.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] High-side injection is commonly used in broadcast receivers because it results in a more practical tuning range for the oscillator.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The mixer processes all signals present at its input, including adjacent channels and strong out-of-band signals.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] After conversion, the IF filter selects the desired component at $f_{\mathrm {IF} }$ and rejects the others.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This separation of frequency conversion and selectivity is a key advantage over earlier tuned radio-frequency (TRF) designs.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In vacuum-tube receivers, the oscillator and mixer functions were often combined in a single device, such as a pentagrid converter, reducing component count and cost.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The mixing stage is sometimes referred to as the *first detector*, while the demodulator that recovers the modulation at the IF is called the *second detector*.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In receivers with multiple conversion stages, these terms extend to *third detector* and beyond.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The stages of an intermediate-frequency amplifier ("IF amplifier" or "IF strip") are tuned to a fixed frequency that does not change as the receiving frequency changes.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This simplifies optimization of the amplifier and its associated filters.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The IF amplifier is selective around its center frequency $f_{\mathrm {IF} }$ .
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Because this frequency is fixed, the stages can be carefully adjusted for best performance, a process known as alignment.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Most of the gain of the receiver ocours in the IF stage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early receivers used LC tuned circuits for IF filtering, usually double-tuned, meaning two LC circuits per stage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Later designs employed mechanical and crystal filters for improved selectivity and stability.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In early designs, the IF center frequency $f_{\mathrm {IF} }$ was typically chosen to be lower than the range of received frequencies $f_{\mathrm {RF} }$ , since high selectivity is easier to achieve at lower frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Standard intermediate frequencies include 455 kHz for medium-wave AM receivers, 10.7 MHz for broadcast FM, 38.9 MHz (Europe) or 45 MHz (United States) for television, and 70 MHz for satellite and terrestrial microwave systems.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The widespread use of these values led to de facto standardization of IF components.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In early superheterodyne receivers, the IF stage was sometimes implemented as a regenerative circuit, providing both gain and selectivity with fewer components.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Such receivers were referred to as super-gainers or regenerodynes.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A related technique is the Q multiplier, which increases the effective selectivity of an IF stage by controlled feedback.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The IF stage includes a filter and/or multiple tuned circuits to provide the required selectivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The passband is chosen to accommodate the bandwidth of the desired signal, while attenuating adjacent channels.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Ideally, the filter provides high attenuation outside the passband while maintaining a relatively flat response across the signal spectrum.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Reduction of bandwidth or uneven response can degrade sound fidelity; excessive bandwidth or shallow roll-off permits interference from adjacent channels.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This selectivity may be obtained using one or more dual-tuned IF transformers, a quartz crystal filter, or a multipole ceramic filter.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In some receivers the IF bandwidth is adjustable, allowing a trade-off between fidelity and noise or interference rejection.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In television receivers, the IF filter must produce the asymmetrical response required for vestigial sideband reception, as used in systems such as NTSC, first standardized in the United States in 1941.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By the 1980s, multi-component LC filters were increasingly replaced by precision electromechanical surface acoustic wave (SAW) filters.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] SAW filters can be manufactured to tight tolerances, are stable in operation, and are well suited to high-volume production.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The received signal is processed by the demodulator stage where the audio signal (or other baseband signal) is recovered and further amplified.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] AM demodulation requires envelope detection, which can be achieved by means of rectification and a low-pass filter to remove remnants of the intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] FM signals may be detected using a discriminator, ratio detector, or phase-locked loop.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Continuous wave and single sideband signals require a product detector using a beat frequency oscillator, or other techniques used for different types of modulation.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The resulting audio signal (for instance) is then amplified and drives a loudspeaker.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] With high-side injection, in which the local-oscillator frequency is above the received signal, the resulting intermediate-frequency spectrum is reversed.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This spectral inversion must be allowed for when receiving modulation formats in which the distinction between upper and lower sidebands is important, such as single-sideband modulation.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In many receivers designed to cover a wide frequency range, a first intermediate frequency higher than the received frequency is used in a double-conversion architecture.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This approach improves image rejection and allows more practical local oscillator tuning ranges.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] For example, the Rohde & Schwarz EK-070 VLF/HF receiver covers 10 kHz to 30 MHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The input is mixed to a first IF of 81.4 MHz, followed by a second IF of 1.4 MHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The first local oscillator therefore tunes from 81.4 to 111.4 MHz, a practical range for a stable oscillator, while the second local oscillator is fixed at 80 MHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] If the same RF range were converted directly to 1.4 MHz, the local oscillator would need to tune from 1.4 to 31.4 MHz, requiring an impractically wide tuning range for a single tuned circuit.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By converting first to a high IF, image rejection is simplified and oscillator design is eased.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] For example, with a 1 MHz input signal, the first LO is at 82.4 MHz and the image occurs at $f_{\mathrm {RF} }+2f_{\mathrm {IF} }=163.8\ {\text{MHz}}$ , which is far removed and easily filtered.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The first IF stage typically includes a narrow filter (for example, a crystal filter with a bandwidth of about 12 kHz), which limits the signal bandwidth before further conversion and attenuates many potential interferers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This reduces overload and intermodulation in subsequent stages.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A second conversion then translates the signal to a lower IF (for example, mixing 81.4 MHz with 80 MHz to produce 1.4 MHz), where higher selectivity can be obtained.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In amateur radio receivers, intermediate frequencies around 9 MHz are commonly used, as they allow practical crystal filter implementations and convenient frequency planning with acceptable image separation.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Analyses of receiver performance and architecture trade-offs, including the impact of conversion strategy on dynamic range and interference handling, are discussed in the technical literature.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Microprocessor technology allows replacing the superheterodyne receiver design by a software-defined radio architecture, where the IF processing after the initial IF filter is implemented in software.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This technique is already in use in certain designs, such as very low-cost FM radios incorporated into mobile phones, since the system already has the necessary microprocessor.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] By converting signals to a fixed intermediate frequency (IF), the superheterodyne improved sensitivity, selectivity, and frequency stability compared with earlier designs.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early superheterodyne receivers required more vacuum tubes than competing designs, which increased cost and complexity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As tube performance improved and manufacturing scaled during the 1920s and 1930s, this disadvantage diminished, and with the introduction of transistors the additional circuit complexity became negligible in most applications.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The remaining limitations arise from the frequency conversion process itself.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Mixing produces undesired responses, including the image frequency, which must be suppressed by RF filtering.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] It also introduces spurious signals and adds noise, while imperfections in the local oscillator further degrade performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] These effects set practical limits on receiver performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A fundamental limitation of the superheterodyne is the image frequency: an undesired signal offset from the desired signal by twice the intermediate frequency, which is also converted to the same IF and cannot be distinguished by the IF filter alone.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] For example, a receiver tuned to 660 kHz (such as WFAN in New York) with a 455 kHz IF and high-side injection uses a local oscillator at 1115 kHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A signal at 1570 kHz, also 455 kHz away from the oscillator, will produce the same IF and can interfere with reception.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] 1570 kHz was historically occupied by high-power XERF, making the effect readily observable.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Image response is reduced by RF filtering ahead of the mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Early receivers, which often used low IF frequencies due to tube limitations, required multiple tuned RF stages to suppress images.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Later designs reduced the problem by using higher first IF frequencies or multiple frequency conversions, increasing the separation between the desired signal and its image.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The ability of a receiver to reject interfering signals at the image frequency is measured by the image rejection ratio.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This is the ratio (in decibels) of the output of the receiver from a signal at the received frequency, to its output for an equal-strength signal at the image frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] When the mixer is not a perfect multiplier, mixing produces additional components of the form *m*fRF ± *n*fLO, where *m* and *n* are integers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Any of these falling within the IF passband appear as spurious signals ("spurs") at the output.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] For example, consider an AM receiver tuned to 1000 kHz with a 455 kHz IF and a local oscillator at 1455 kHz.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] A signal at 955 kHz can produce a spur at the IF through a higher-order mixing product (2 × 955 − 1455 = 455 kHz).
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This occurs because the mixer generates harmonics and intermodulation products in addition to the desired sum and difference frequencies.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Channel spacing in broadcast bands (such as 10 kHz in the United States) often places such spurs slightly offset (e.g., by 5 kHz), so they may be partially attenuated by the IF filter but can still cause audible interference.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] These responses arise because practical mixers have a nonlinear transfer function rather than acting as ideal multipliers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Modern balanced and double-balanced mixer designs reduce the amplitude of many unwanted products, and integrated circuit implementations achieve improved spur performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The beam-deflection tube (e.g., the 7360) approached more ideal multiplication and reduced intermodulation effects.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Stray radiation from the local oscillator can be difficult to suppress below levels detectable by a nearby receiver, and below levels required by standards organizations.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] When the local oscillator signal reaches the antenna the receiver acts as a low-power CW transmitter, potentially interfering with other receivers.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This problem was significant in early radio.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Local oscillator radiation is most prominent in receivers where the antenna is coupled directly to the mixer, which also receives the local oscillator signal, rather than in designs that include an intervening RF amplifier stage.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] It is therefore more significant in inexpensive receivers and in receivers operating at very high frequencies (especially microwave), where RF amplifier stages are more difficult to implement.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In intelligence operations, local oscillator radiation can be used to detect a covert receiver and its operating frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The method was used by MI5 during Operation RAFTER.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This same technique is also used in radar detector detectors by traffic police in jurisdictions where radar detectors are illegal.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Mixing degrades the signal-to-noise ratio, which is unavoidable.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] If the desired input to the mixer is at 1000 kHz and the local oscillator is at 1455 kHz, noise at both 1000 kHz and at the image frequency of 1910 kHz will be translated to the 455 kHz intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Noise from the image band therefore appears at the output even for an ideal mixer.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In practical receivers, the mixer also contributes noise, and its conversion loss reduces the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Subsequent gain amplifies both signal and noise, preserving this reduced ratio.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This is an inherent consequence of frequency conversion and sets a lower bound on achievable sensitivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The frequency conversion process does not improve the signal-to-noise ratio; it translates both the desired signal and any noise present at the input to the IF frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] In addition, the local oscillator (LO) contributes its own noise, primarily as phase noise, a side effect of practical oscillators.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] During mixing, this phase noise appears as sidebands around the converted signal at the intermediate frequency.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] This effect, known as *reciprocal mixing*, arises because the mixer combines not only the desired input signal with the LO, but also mixes LO noise with signals present at the input.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] As a result, strong signals on adjacent frequencies can be converted into noise within the receiver passband, degrading sensitivity and selectivity.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] The phase noise of the local oscillator is therefore a critical parameter in receiver performance.
[src:mixer-rf/image-frequency] Oscillator design, device noise, and circuit topology all influence phase noise.
